n Jose State University]] |- | colspan=2 | Parry broke his leg in a game for SJSU; a week later, following an infection and nerve and arterial damage, it was amputated. Three years later, Parry, wearing a prosthetic leg, returned to the field for SJSU. |- | 2004 || Tim Frisby, [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|University of South Carolina]] |- | colspan=2 | Frisby walked on at [[wide receiver]] for the Gamecocks at age 39, after a 20-year career in the [[United States Army|Army]]. |- | 2005 || [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane University]] |- | colspan=2 | In the wake of [[Hurricane Katrina]], and [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on Tulane University|the closure of the campus for the fall semester]], Tulane was forced to play all 11 of its games on the road. |- | 2006 || [[Patrick Henry Hughes]], [[The University of Louisville Marching Band|University of Louisville]] |- | colspan=2 | Hughes, Louisville's second recipient, is a member of Louisville's marching band, even though he was born with no eyes and cannot straighten his arms and legs. He shared the award with his father, Patrick John Hughes. |- | 2007 || Zerbin Singleton, [[Navy Midshipmen football|United States Naval Academy]] |- | colspan=2 | Singleton overcame personal tragedy and a broken collarbone that initially prevented him from enrolling in Annapolis. |- | 2008 || [[Tim Tebow]], [[Florida Gators football|University of Florida]] |- | colspan=2 | Tebow was honored for his "countless hours preaching and providing support to less fortunate people, capitalizing on virtually every opportunity to touch the lives of others." |- | 2009 || [[Mark Herzlich]], [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]] |- | colspan=2 | Herzlich was honored for his fight to overcome [[Ewing's sarcoma]], and inspiring his teammates and other football teams to raise money for cancer research. |- | 2010 || [[D. J. Williams (tight end)|D.J. Williams]], [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|University of Arkansas]] |- | colspan=2 | Williams, his mother and two sisters fled their home in [[Dallas]] to escape a drug-addicted and abusive father. They landed in Arkansas, where they put down roots of their own. Williams used his stature on the Razorbacks football team and spread his story and message to others in groups like the [[Big Brothers Big Sisters of America|Big Brothers and Big Sisters]] program, the local [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys and Girls Clubs]] and [[Arkansas Children's Hospital|Children's Hospital]]. |- | 2011 || [[2011 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]] |- | colspan=2 | The Alabama football team was honored for their collective efforts to assist in the rebuilding of [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] following the [[2011 Super Outbreak#Tuscaloosa/Birmingham tornado|April 27, 2011, tornado that devastated the city]]. The award was accepted by [[long snapper]] [[Carson Tinker]] who suffered a broken wrist when he was thrown from his home during the storm, with his girlfriend being one of the 43 fatalities attributed to the storm in Tuscaloosa.<ref name="2011Spirit">{{cite news |title=Alabama wins Disney Spirit Award for efforts following storm |url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20111122/news/111129968 |first=Tommy |last=Deas |newspaper=The Tuscaloosa News |date=November 22, 2011 |accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> |- |2012|| [[Nate Boyer]], [[Texas Longhorns football|University of Texas at Austin]] |- | colspan=2 | The Longhorns long snapper was recognized for his service as a Green Beret and his work with Darfur refugee camps. |- |2013|| [[Devon Walker]], [[Tulane Green Wave]] |- | colspan=2 | Devon Walker has "exhibited tremendous courage and perseverance following a severe spinal cord injury last season, and has become a motivational figure for the football team, the university and the New Orleans community."<ref>http://disneysportsnews.com/2013/11/22/tulane-universitys-devon-walker-to-accept-2013-disney-spirit-award/</ref> |- |2014|| [[Sterling Shepard]], [[Bob Stoops]]; [[Oklahoma Sooners football|University of Oklahoma]] |- | colspan=2 | Stoops and Shepard formed an inspirational bond from tragic death of former Sooners receiver, and Sterling's father, Derrick Shepard 15 years ago. Derrick Shepard was graduate assistant coach and former receiver at the university. Stoops became a father figure to the then six year old Sterling.<ref>http://disneysportsnews.com/fact-sheets/2014/11/27/disney-sports-spirit-award-and-the-home-depot-college-football-awards-show/</ref> |- |2015|| [[Hank Goff]], [[Concordia University (Saint Paul, Minnesota)]] |- | colspan=2 | "After a nine-month combat stint in Afghanistan in April 2008, Goff struggled with post-combat trauma and post-traumatic stress disorder, which led to depression and excessive drinking. It was a dark period during which Goff said he felt like a monster. Goff credits football with helping him find his way back to the light. Today, at the advanced football age of 28, Goff has become a stellar Division II football player (this year, he was a preseason second-team All-American) who has begun to counsel fellow veterans coping with similar post-war challenges."<ref>http://cugoldenbears.com/news/2015/12/1/FB_1201150145.aspx?path=football</ref> |- |2016 || [[James Conner (American football)|James Conner]], [[2016 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|University of Pittsburgh]] |- | colspan=2 | Returned from a December 2015 diagnosis of [[Hodgkin lymphoma]] and subsequent chemotherapy to run for over 1,000 yards and 20 touchdowns in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/culture/the-buzz/article/18238527/holly-rowe-shelley-smith-present-james-conner-disney-sports-spirit-award |title=Holly Rowe, Shelley Smith present James Conner with Disney Sports Spirit Award |first=Matt |last=Eisenberg |publisher=[[ESPN.com|ESPNW]] |date=December 8, 2016 |accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref> |- |2017 || [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|University of Iowa]] |- | colspan=2 | Created the [[Iowa Hawkeyes football#Kinnick Wave|"Kinnick Wave"]], in which fans turn toward the [[University of Iowa Children's Hospital|children's hospital]] that overlooks [[Kinnick Stadium]] and wave toward patients and their families watching the game from the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2017/11/disney-salutes-the-kinnick-wave-with-the-2017-disney-sports-spirit-award/ |title=Disney Salutes the ‘Kinnick Wave’ with the 2017 Disney Sports Spirit Award |first=Darrell |last=Fry |publisher=[[Walt Disney World]] |date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> |- |2018 |Tyler Trent, [[Purdue University]] |- | colspan="2" |Tyler gained notoriety with the university after receiving chemotherapy and camped outside [[Ross–Ade Stadium|Ross Ade Stadium]] before the 2017 homecoming game. In 2018, he grew to national lore by predicting [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]] would beat then ranked #2 [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] in Tyler's first game back to campus since entering hospice care. Tyler celebrated with the team on the field and in the locker room after the win. Tyler's story has generated thousands of donations for cancer research and created an [https://giving.purdue.edu/s/1461/campaign/start.aspx?sid=1461&gid=1010&pgid=9633 endowment with the Purdue Cancer Center]. |}
